{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17521666","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17521666"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:35:50+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:35:50+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13691"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13691","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13691"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.15,0.23,0.34,0.16,0.11]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6299"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65065"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6299","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6299"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13691"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50501"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"316"},{"type":"tags","id":"912"},{"type":"tags","id":"1177"},{"type":"tags","id":"2255"},{"type":"tags","id":"2401"},{"type":"tags","id":"2746"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"6534"},{"type":"tags","id":"8118"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"11774"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22641"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43432"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44601"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65065","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/65065"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 56-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a one-week history of rapidly worsening shortness of breath. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears distressed with a pulse rate of 90/min, blood pressure 160/95 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, SpO2 95% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. He has facial swelling and distended neck veins. Cardiorespiratory examination reveals reduced air entry in the right upper zone. Investigations show:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHaemoglobin 110 g/L (130-180)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhite cell count 8.0 x10^9/L (4.0-11.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPlatelets 350 x10^9/L (150-400)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPT 16 seconds (11-13.5)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAPTT 38 seconds (25-35)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ED-dimer 4.5 mg/L (\u0026lt;0.5)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETSH 0.2 mIU/L (0.4-4.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFree T4 12 pmol/L (10-20)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHis chest X-ray is shown below (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely underlying cause for his symptoms?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Lymphoma","Thymic carcinoma","Primary lung cancer","Neuroendocrine tumour","Thyroid carcinoma"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic symptoms and signs of superior vena cava (SVC) obstruction syndrome, which is a medical emergency characterised by facial swelling, dyspnoea, and distended neck veins. The acute onset dyspnoea is most likley due to the SVC obstruction itself rather that the mass in this case. The most common cause of SVC obstruction is \u003Cstrong\u003Eprimary lung cancer\u003C/strong\u003E. In this case a CT scan was performed (Image) which revealed superior vena cava obstruction with significant mediastinal and hilar lymphadenopathy, with a biopsy performed which demonstrated small-cell lung carcinoma. Small-cell lung cancer is known for its rapid growth and tendency to cause mediastinal compression. Although this patient is younger than the typical lung cancer demographic and has no reported smoking history, primary lung cancer should still be the leading differential in a patient with SVC obstruction. Diagnosis and treatment of the underlying cause are urgent to relieve the obstruction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EExamination reveals reduced air entry in the right upper zone, consistent with a space-occupying lesion compressing the right main bronchus. Investigations show a mild normocytic anaemia, which can occur in malignancy. The prolonged PT and APTT also suggest a consumptive coagulopathy, which is common in advanced malignancy. The grossly elevated D-dimer is a non-specific marker of increased fibrin degradation, seen in malignancy, inflammation and thrombosis. The chest X-ray shows a right hilar mass, which in the context of SVC obstruction is highly suggestive of lung cancer. The thyroid function tests show a low TSH with normal free T4, consistent with sick euthyroid syndrome which can occur in severe illness such as advanced malignancy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInitial management of suspected malignant SVC obstruction involves high-dose corticosteroids to reduce inflammation and oedema. Definitive treatment depends on the underlying cause but may involve radiotherapy, chemotherapy, endovascular stenting or a combination of these.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELymphoma\u003C/strong\u003E is the second most common cause of SVC obstruction after lung cancer. It would more typically present in a younger patient and may have associated lymphadenopathy, night sweats and weight loss. However, lymphoma is less likely to cause unilateral hilar opacification.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThymic carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E is a rare cause of superior vena cava obstruction. It typically presents with anterior mediastinal mass rather than unilateral hilar enlargement. Thymic carcinomas are much less common than lung cancer.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENeuroendocrine tumours\u003C/strong\u003E can rarely cause superior vena cava obstruction, but they are much less common than lung cancer and typically present with other symptoms such as flushing or diarrhoea.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe thyroid function tests are not suggestive of \u003Cstrong\u003Ethyroid carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E. Thyroid carcinoma can very rarely cause mediastinal compression if it extends retrosternally. However, it would be unlikely to present with such rapid onset of symptoms and would usually be clinically apparent on neck examination. Thyroid malignancies are also much less common than lung cancer.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Superior vena cava obstruction syndrome is often caused by malignancies such as lung cancer or lymphoma.","Symptoms of superior vena cava obstruction include facial swelling, dyspnoea, and distended neck veins.","Management of superior vena cava obstruction involves high-dose steroids, and may require radiotherapy, chemotherapy, or stenting depending on the underlying cause."],"references":["Azizad S, Sannananja B, Restrepo CS. Solid Tumors of the Mediastinum in Adults. Semin Ultrasound CT MR. 2016;37:196-211. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/27261345/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50501"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13691"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20651"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20697"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20651","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20651"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https: